  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Designing the Decoder Utility**\n\nI\'m focusing on designing the aviation weather decoder tool. The immediate goal is to create a parser for METAR and TAF reports. I\'ve decided to first understand the METAR and TAF formats. Now I\'ll create a robust parser in TypeScript, specifically in a file located at `/src/utils/metarDecoder.ts`.\n\n\n**Analyzing the METAR Format**\n\nI\'m now diving deeper into the METAR format to dissect its components. I\'ve begun to identify the key elements: station identifiers, time stamps, wind information (direction, speed, gusts), visibility data (statute miles or metric), and cloud cover details. I\'m focusing on parsing each of these components accurately, in preparation for the decoder implementation. Next up, it\'s parsing the cloud formations.\n\n\n**Deciphering Visibility Data**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on visibility decoding. I\'m taking into account varied representations in METAR reports: statute miles like `4SM`, fractions such as `1 1/2SM`, and even metric values. I have to make sure my parser correctly interprets and converts all these formats. I\'m focusing on the potential for \"less than\" notations as well, such as `M1/4SM`.\n\n\n**Parsing Cloud Formations**\n\nI\'m now deep in the complexities of cloud cover representations within METAR reports. I\'m focusing on deciphering the codes: `FEW`, `SCT`, `BKN`, `OVC`, and the special cases of `NSC`, `CLR`, `SKC`, and `VV`. I\'m paying close attention to height annotations (e.g., `015`, `035`, `110`) and modifiers like `CB` and `TCU`. The goal is a highly flexible parser.\n\n\n**Implementing Trend Charts**\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating trend charts using Recharts for wind and visibility. My thought is that historical data would be incredibly useful, perhaps by keeping a history of fetched data or displaying trends using TAF forecasts. The key here is the TAF forecast periods, allowing me to plot a timeline of forecast conditions, which I\'ll render in Recharts. This is a big step towards a professional-grade aviation weather tool.\n\n\n**Integrating API Endpoints**\n\nNow, I\'m working to integrate the aviationweather.gov API endpoints into the tool. I\'m focusing on fetching both METAR and TAF data using the provided URLs. I will verify that the JSON response structure is as expected, especially the format of the METAR data, to prepare the parsing process.\n\n\n**Combining Data & Parsing**\n\nI\'m now integrating both the API-provided parsed fields and my parser\'s output, especially for the raw METAR/TAF strings. This will allow for a comprehensive, in-depth decoding process that leverages both approaches, providing a highly detailed and robust output. I am taking advantage of the parsed values provided by the API, but my own parser adds a level of expert detail to the aviation domain knowledge. I will also be looking at how to parse the TAF reports using a similar approach.\n\n\n**Defining Aviation Types**\n\nI\'m now defining the data types for decoded METAR and TAF reports in `/src/utils/aviationTypes.ts`, essential for our decoding modules. I\'m focusing on key METAR elements like station ID, time, and wind, while also creating the foundation for parsing raw strings, which will be the heart of our resilient decoder. The `rawOb` and `rawTAF` fields will be critical. I\'m thinking about how to handle missing fields gracefully by implementing fallback strategies. This professional-grade approach ensures robustness. Next, I\'ll start building the parsing functions.\n\n\n**Refining Data Structures**\n\nI\'m now refining the data structures in `aviationTypes.ts` with aviation-specific types. I\'m focusing on adding `colorClass` and `label` properties for wind, visibility, and flight category, and also the `fogRisk` flag for temperature. I\'m also building out an object that contains weather phenomena, such as `haze` and `drizzle`. The next step is to create a complete decoder.\n\n\n**Calculating Flight Categories**\n\nI\'m now drafting a helper function to accurately calculate flight categories, considering both ceiling height and visibility. My focus is on implementing VFR, MVFR, IFR, and LIFR rules precisely, incorporating the definitions of ceiling, and also reviewing that FEW and SCT cloud layers do not constitute a ceiling. This will be key to correct operation.\n\n\n**Decoding Weather Phenomena**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a weather phenomena decoder. I\'m building a mapping of codes to their meanings. This includes descriptors (like `TS` for Thunderstorms, `SH` for Showers), precipitation types (e.g., `RA` for Rain, `DZ` for Drizzle), and obscurations (e.g., `FG` for Fog, `HZ` for Haze). I am working to make this parsing process robust.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create the `/src/utils/aviationTypes.ts` file to specify the core types and interfaces for decoded METAR and TAF data. This ensures rigid type-safety and structured data sharing across the briefing components."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 20
      nanos: 436878258
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
