  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Refining METAR Decoding**\n\nI\'m currently creating the METAR decoder function, `decodeMETAR`. It appears that the API provides the METAR as JSON, so I can use my own decoder to process either the raw string or the JSON. This is an improvement. I need to make sure the process handles both types of input for flexibility.\n\n\n**Designing METAR Parser**\n\nI\'m now designing the METAR parser in a step-by-step fashion. I\'m focusing on parsing key elements: the ICAO code (usually the first word), the observation time (a word ending in \"Z,\" which needs UTC formatting), and the wind data (e.g., `27015G22`). I\'m also planning to create a utility to format the observation time and ensure it is not stale using UTC time differences, to ensure robustness.\n\n\n**Analyzing Wind Data**\n\nI\'ve tested a regex `/(\\d{3}|VRB)(\\d{2,3})(G\\d{2,3})?KT/` for wind data, successfully extracting direction, speed, and gusts. I\'m noting VRB for variable direction, handling calm winds (00000KT). The implementation\'s wind color-coding scheme, based on speed and gusts, is ready. I\'m now working to ensure the parser\'s logic can consistently handle these varied wind conditions.\n\n**Determining Visibility Parsing**\n\nI\'m now determining how to parse visibility data. I\'m checking tokens containing \"SM\" or \"/SM\", accounting for fractional representations like \"1/2SM\". I\'ve planned to build a robust token parser, which analyzes a token to extract visibility values, including combined values such as \"1 1/2SM\".\n\n\n**Parsing Visibility Logic**\n\nI\'m now building the logic to extract visibility from various METAR formats. My current focus is on handling both statute miles (SM) and meter-based visibility values. I\'ve successfully defined steps for extracting values from tokens like \"10SM,\" \"1/2SM,\" and combined values such as \"1 1/2SM\". I\'m also managing the special case with \"M\" for \"less than.\" Additionally, I am designing for a plain-English label and color-coding, based on ranges.\n\n\n**Decoding Cloud Cover**\n\nI\'m now implementing the cloud layer decoding. I\'m applying a regex to extract cloud coverage (FEW, SCT, BKN, OVC, VV), height in hundreds of feet, and special indicators like CB or TCU. I\'m also handling \"CLR\", \"SKC\", \"NSC\", and \"NCD\". I\'m making sure to factor in that cloud types like CB/TCU get a red warning flag in the results. I\'m also ensuring height conversions for both feet and meters, to be precise. I\'m also noting that vertical visibility, such as `VV002`, will be treated as a cloud layer at 200 feet.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now create `/src/utils/metarDecoder.ts` to implement the rule-based parser for METAR strings, decoding all the elements like Wind, Visibility, Clouds, Temperature, Dewpoint spread, Pressure, Weather Phenomena, and Flight Category. This is fully client-side, self-contained, and extremely robust, with support for the CAVOK condition, variable winds (VRB), vertical visibility (VV), and negative temperatures (M)."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 10
      nanos: 562446161
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
