  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Simplifying Page Structure**\n\nI\'m focusing on page structure and routing. I realized there\'s no need for an overly complex setup. Let\'s keep it clean, as there\'s no need for a deep hierarchy right now. I\'m taking a look at the pages requested, specifically the home/search page.\n\n\n**Designing the Homepage**\n\nI\'ve sketched out the initial design for the homepage. It will feature a full dark hero section with a large, centered search bar that prompts for an airport ICAO code. A \"Get Briefing\" button in sky blue and quick-access buttons for popular airports will sit below. A concise tagline and footer complete the layout.\n\n\n**Adding Charts and About**\n\nI\'m now integrating charts for wind and visibility trends into Section C, as the TAF forecast data lends itself well to visualization. I\'ve also written an initial \"About\" page, highlighting my background and the app\'s purpose, with tech stack badges and a GitHub link. Finally, I\'ve decided to add a persistent navigation bar with \"Home\", \"About\" and \"Briefing\" tabs.\n\n\n**Implementing Navigation Structure**\n\nI\'ve worked out the tab structure. Displaying the \"Home,\" \"Briefing,\" or \"About\" pages based on `activeTab` is straightforward now. The navbar will ensure fluid user navigation, with a professional look. I am very pleased with this solution.\n\nI\'m starting to build a high-contrast Recharts trend chart, and it will be a perfect fit in the dark theme. The data will come from the TAF periods, with `timeStart`, `speedKt`, `gustsKt`, and `distanceSm` used to create an array of data points for visualization.\n\n\n**Visualizing Wind and Visibility**\n\nI\'m now implementing the wind speed/gusts and visibility charts. The elegance lies in using Recharts for area/line charts, styled with SkyClear\'s colors. Wind and gusts will be sky blue and amber, respectively, while visibility will be green, all against a dark navy background. I am implementing TAF checks to ensure a robust system, with a friendly message for unavailable forecasts.\n\n\n**Defining the UI Palette**\n\nI\'ve established the color palette to maintain a consistent style. Sky blue is assigned to primary actions, amber for warnings, red indicates danger or IFR, and green shows VFR conditions. White or light gray will be used for text. I\'ve designed a card-based layout with subtle borders in a dark gray. Now I need to build smooth loading skeletons and ensure mobile-friendliness alongside desktop optimization. Also, no emojis! I will use `lucide-react` icons.\n\nI also made a preliminary check for suitable `lucide-react` icons. I\'m focusing on icons such as `Plane`, `Search`, `RefreshCw`, `Wind`, `Eye`, `Cloud`, `CloudRain`, `CloudLightning`, `Thermometer`, `Gauge`, `Compass`, `Activity`, `Clock`, `AlertTriangle`, `ShieldAlert`, `BookOpen`, and `Info`.\n\n\n**Adding Footer and Pages**\n\nI\'m now integrating the updated footer with the \"Built by Nellutla Pravaltej\" message, highlighting my student pilot status and aerospace ambitions. I\'m also preparing to create the main components: `Navbar`, `HomeView`, `BriefingView`, `AboutView`, and `SkeletonLoader`, ensuring a well-structured application. I\'ll review and load the fonts too. I\'m looking for the perfect icons. Specifically, I\'m considering `ChevronRight` or `History`, `ArrowRight`, `Book` or `GraduationCap`, and `Github`.\n\n\n**Importing Fonts and Typography**\n\nI\'m now integrating fonts into the project. I\'ve decided to import \"Inter\" and \"Space Grotesk\" from Google Fonts into `src/index.css` using `@import url(...)`. I\'m also reviewing and adopting the specified Tailwind CSS typography rules for headings and data/code elements, and I will replace the existing `src/index.css` file with the updated content.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will modify `/src/index.css` to load clean typography (the \"Inter\" font for UI elements and \"Space Grotesk\" for displays and numbers) and configure them in Tailwind CSS v4 using the `@theme` directive. This will give the application a refined Electronic Flight Bag (EFB) look."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 11
      nanos: 827048856
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
