  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Celebrating Rapid Compilation**\n\nI\'m thrilled with the blazing-fast compile time \342\200\223 sub-6 seconds! I\'ve successfully crafted `/src/utils/aviationTypes.ts`, complete with typed interfaces for METAR data, TAF forecasts, time periods, and weather conditions. Also, I\'ve got `/src/utils/metarDecoder` ready. Things are really progressing nicely, and I\'m very excited.\n\n\n**Developing Robust Aviation Decoding**\n\nI\'ve just finished a professional-grade, rule-based METAR decoder in `/src/utils/metarDecoder.ts`. It handles numerous edge cases like calm winds, negative temperatures, visibility units, and cloud layers with hazardous indicators, accurately computing flight categories. The `/src/utils/tafDecoder.ts` file is now complete, handling horizontal TAF timelines by parsing distinct time periods by reusing the METAR logic. API calls are now handled with `/src/utils/api.ts`.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I have successfully built and verified **SkyClear \342\200\224 Aviation Weather Briefing Tool**, a professional glass-cockpit Electronic Flight Bag (EFB) web utility designed for student and licensed pilots to decode live weather conditions.\n\nHere is a summary of the architectural and design implementations:\n\n### \360\237\216\250 Visual & Cockpit Design\n- **EFB Glass-Cockpit Theme**: Built on a solid deep-navy canvas (`#0A0F1E`) with elegant border structures (`#1E293B`), utilizing high-contrast sky blue (`#38BDF8`) for primary commands, amber (`#F59E0B`) for weather warnings, red (`#EF4444`) for convective hazards/IFR rules, and green (`#22C55E`) for VFR statuses.\n- **Clean Typography**: Loaded **Space Grotesk** for tactical numeric values and display elements, paired with **Inter** for descriptions and **JetBrains Mono** for raw report data blocks.\n- **Aesthetic Precision**: Zero emojis are used in the user interface to ensure the software matches professional cockpit avionics. Custom-designed, subtle scrollbars provide a sleek desktop browsing experience.\n\n### \342\232\231\357\270\217 Core Technical Modules\n1. **Rule-Based METAR Decoder (`/src/utils/metarDecoder.ts`)**:\n   - Parses raw METAR strings using a state-machine with regular expressions.\n   - Translates winds, handling calm conditions (`00000KT`), variable vectors (`VRB`), and wind speed thresholds.\n   - Formats visibility in miles (SM) and kilometers (KM), rating conditions dynamically (Excellent to Very Poor).\n   - Decodes temperature and dewpoints (handling negative `M` indicators), calculating the dewpoint spread and highlighting fog probability if the spread is under 3\302\260C.\n   - Categorizes flights according to official FAA rules (VFR, MVFR, IFR, LIFR) by calculating ceiling thresholds (based strictly on broken `BKN`, overcast `OVC`, or vertical visibility `VV` layers).\n2. **Horizon TAF Timeline Parser (`/src/utils/tafDecoder.ts`)**:\n   - Isolates the Terminal Aerodrome Forecast into distinct time intervals.\n   - Parses transition segments (`FM`, `BECMG`, `TEMPO`, `PROB30/40`) and maps their respective flight rules.\n3. **Robust API Connector (`/src/utils/api.ts`)**:\n   - Connects directly to the live, free NOAA / AviationWeather.gov stream.\n   - Implements a 10-second `AbortController` timeout and handles incorrect ICAO inputs or missing observations gracefully.\n4. **Interactive Dashboard View (`/src/components/BriefingView.tsx`)**:\n   - **Briefing Summary**: Synthesizes the parsed METAR values into a natural English paragraph.\n   - **Horizontal Timeline**: Displays forecast periods as chronologically organized, horizontally scrollable cards.\n   - **Recharts Trend Lines**: Renders two distinct graphical charts visualizing the wind velocity trend (including gusts) and visibility miles across the 24-to-30-hour forecast horizon.\n   - **Pilot Reference Card**: A static reference panel detailing meteorological principles, fog indices, and VFR flight rules.\n5. **Portfolio & Biography (`/src/components/AboutView.tsx`)**:\n   - Showcases your credentials as a student pilot and aerospace engineering applicant, highlighting your applications to **Purdue, MIT, and Stanford**. Contains clear, technical descriptions of the project\'s engineering values and software stack.\n6. **Smooth Loading Skeleton (`/src/components/SkeletonLoader.tsx`)**:\n   - Provides a cohesive, pulsing SVG card grid matching the cockpit layout to prevent sudden page flickering during network latency.\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 2
      nanos: 128409490
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
