  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Flight Categories**\n\nI\'ve successfully confirmed that `getFlightCategoryDetails` is returning unique objects for each flight category, complete with styling details like background and border classes. I\'m now examining the requested styling to see how it\'s being implemented, and whether I can optimize it. I\'m taking a close look at the use of utility classes.\n\n\n**Verifying Style Consistency**\n\nI\'m now diving into the design\'s HTML to check for style conflicts and redundancies. I\'ve spotted a pattern: all detailed metric cards share the same background, border, padding, and rounded corners, which suggests an opportunity for DRY (Don\'t Repeat Yourself) principle implementation. I\'m focusing on the Flight Category card which includes colors dependent on the flight category code. I\'m aiming to write a dynamic converter for this. I will look at how to map the flight category code to the precise hex colors used in the design.\n\n\n**Implementing Sleek Color Themes**\n\nI\'m now implementing the color theming for the sleek interface, focusing on dynamic color mapping based on flight category codes. I\'ve defined the color palettes for VFR, MVFR, IFR, and LIFR, and decided to use Tailwind\'s arbitrary values, such as `border-red-500 bg-red-500/10 text-red-500`, for a cleaner and fully dynamic approach. I\'m aiming for a concise mapping function within `BriefingView.tsx` for easy integration.\n\n\n**Extending Theming Capabilities**\n\nI\'ve realized I can apply these dynamic themes to TAF period cards as well! I\'m expanding the application of color-coding based on flight category to all relevant components, aiming to maintain consistency across the interface. I\'m focusing on the mapping function and its integration to keep the code clean and scalable.\n\n\n**Integrating TAF Theming**\n\nI\'m now integrating the sleek themes into the TAF flight category card styling, aiming for consistent left-border indicators. I\'m taking a close look at `BriefingView.tsx` and focusing on lines 54-528 to refactor it. I am taking a very careful look at the structure, from the back-to-search button to the station header, to ensure its premium design is reflected in the refactor.\n\n\n**Refining Station Header**\n\nI\'m now refining the station header to ensure consistency and visual appeal. I\'ve focused on the design of the ICAO input and status card, paying particular attention to the button for a new briefing. I\'m aiming for a sleek look that matches the other implemented themes and styling.\n\n\n**Enhancing Responsive Header**\n\nI\'m now integrating responsive design principles into the header navigation for an improved mobile experience. My goal is to maintain the accessibility of the back button on smaller screens, and I\'m ensuring all the dynamic states, such as `onRefresh`, `onBackToSearch`, and `metar.icao`, are handled correctly within the design\'s theme. I\'m focusing on ensuring it looks pristine on mobile as a primary concern.\n\n\n**Implementing Raw Displays**\n\nI\'m now integrating the display of raw METAR and TAF data directly into the briefing summary. I\'ve designed sections for these within the existing layout, with clear labels and a monospace font for readability. I\'ve included a no-TAF message for clarity if the forecast is unavailable.\n\n\n**Optimizing Grid Layout**\n\nI\'m now refining the main grid layout to be responsive. I\'ve switched from `grid-cols-12` to `grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-12` for improved adaptability. I\'m ensuring the left section (METAR decoder) occupies `lg:col-span-8` and the right section (Category & Forecast) occupies `lg:col-span-4`. I\'m also ensuring the detailed metrics grid scales smoothly with `grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3` inside.\n\n\n**Refining Data Displays**\n\nI\'m now refining the METAR wind display. I\'ve focused on ensuring the color coding for wind conditions aligns precisely with established flight category thresholds. Specifically, I\'m integrating the wind data using the proper color class based on the category. I\'m ensuring all the dynamic states, such as `wind.isCalm` and `wind.direction`, are handled correctly. I\'m focusing on ensuring it looks pristine within the premium design.\n\n\n**Adjusting Wind and Visibility**\n\nI\'m now integrating the wind display, meticulously ensuring precise color-coding based on flight category thresholds, and integrating data using the appropriate color class. I\'m focusing on handling dynamic states like `wind.isCalm` and `wind.direction`, aiming for a premium, pristine visual presentation. I\'m also addressing visibility by aligning color classes correctly.\n\n\n**Refining Cloud and Temperature Displays**\n\nI\'m now refining the cloud layer and temperature displays within the METAR data. I\'m focusing on the visual presentation, ensuring the use of `isHazard` in cloud displays for bold red highlights, and maintaining clear labeling and readability. I\'ve also checked the styling and color for the temperature.\n\n\n**Improving Temperature Displays**\n\nI\'m now refining the temperature and dewpoint display within the METAR data. I\'ve focused on ensuring clear labeling, readability, and a concise layout for temperature, dewpoint, and the spread. I\'m also addressing the fog risk display, applying a pulsating red highlight when necessary and displaying it in green otherwise, keeping the design clean and intuitive.\n\n\n**Refining Alt Altimeter**\n\nI\'m now refining the Alt Altimeter display. I\'ve focused on ensuring clear labeling, readability, and the concise layout for pressure. I\'m also addressing the visual presentation of altimeter, ensuring the design of a premium and intuitive presentation.\n\n\n**Refining Pressure Analysis**\n\nI\'m now integrating pressure analysis into the METAR data display. I\'ve designed a clear section for atmospheric pressure, covering standard, high, and low barometric conditions. I\'ve maintained the dynamic elements, and included descriptive explanations for each pressure type for clarity. I\'m focusing on the visual presentation, and ensuring all states are handled correctly.\n\n\n**Building Forecast Sections**\n\nI\'m now focusing on constructing the forecast (TAF) timeline and pilot notes wrapper. I\'ve designed the visual structure, including the background, border, and rounded corners, to match the overall design theme. I\'ll need to add in the actual TAF data now.\n\n\n**Constructing TAF Styling**\n\nI\'m now styling the TAF period cards and integrating the `getCategorySleekTheme` function. I\'m focusing on applying the correct `border-l-4` color based on the flight category and incorporating the sleek theming, which defines the background color. I\'m reviewing the structure and colors to ensure visual appeal, and that everything is clear to the user.\n\n\n**Implementing Gorgeous Display**\n\nI\'m now integrating the wind display, precisely aligning color-coding with flight category thresholds and implementing data using the correct color class. I\'m focusing on managing dynamic states like `wind.isCalm` and `wind.direction`. I am making sure the design looks premium. Furthermore, I\'m adding `fogRisk` to the pilot notes for a polished design. I am now incorporating design elements for the gorgeous design.\n\n\n**Optimizing Chart Placement**\n\nI\'m now integrating Recharts forecast trend charts into the sleek interface. They\'ll be placed within the left section (`lg:col-span-8`) under the detailed metrics grid for a visually intuitive flow. This placement will enhance the user experience by providing graphical forecasts that complement the tabular data, and it will keep all the data within the same visual block.\n\n\n"
