    summary: "The error message \"Cannot set property fetch of\" typically indicates an attempt to assign a new value to the `fetch` property on an object that either doesn\'t exist, hasn\'t been properly initialized, or, more specifically, is a built-in object with a `fetch` property that cannot be directly overwritten. This is a common JavaScript `TypeError` that manifests as \"Cannot set property \'<property>\' of undefined\" or \"Cannot set property \'<property>\' of null\"[1][2].\n\nHere\'s a breakdown of the potential causes and solutions:\n\n*   **Attempting to overwrite the native `window.fetch` API**: The most likely scenario for this specific error is trying to directly reassign `window.fetch` in a browser environment, as the `Window` object\'s `fetch` property often has only a getter and no setter, preventing direct modification[3][4]. This means you cannot simply write `window.fetch = myCustomFetchFunction`.\n*   **Object is `undefined` or `null`**: This error occurs when you try to set a property on a variable that has not been initialized or assigned a value, meaning it is `undefined` or `null`[1][2]. For example, if you declare `let myObject;` and then try `myObject.fetch = someValue;`, you will encounter this error because `myObject` is `undefined`.\n*   **Common scenarios for uninitialized objects**: This can happen in various real-world applications, particularly when dealing with nested objects, manipulating the Document Object Model (DOM), or handling asynchronous data fetching where an expected object might not yet be available[1].\n\n**To resolve this error, consider the following:**\n\n*   **Avoid directly overwriting `window.fetch`**: If your intention is to intercept or modify `fetch` requests, consider using techniques like monkey-patching (carefully replacing the original function with your own while maintaining a reference to the original) or service workers for more robust request interception.\n*   **Initialize your objects**: Ensure that the object you are trying to set the `fetch` property on is properly initialized before attempting to assign values to its properties. This might involve setting it to an empty object (`{}`) or ensuring a function returns a valid object[2].\n*   **Check for `undefined` or `null`**: Before setting a property, use conditional checks to verify that the object is not `undefined` or `null`[2].\n*   **Use optional chaining**: For accessing nested properties, optional chaining (`?.`) can help prevent errors if an intermediate property in the chain is `null` or `undefined`[2].\n\nA related error, \"Cannot read property \'then\' of undefined,\" often occurs when a `fetch` call or another asynchronous function that is expected to return a Promise does not actually do so, leading to an attempt to call `.then()` on an `undefined` value[5][6]. In such cases, ensure that the function explicitly returns the Promise.\n\nSources:\n[1] [medium.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGYGZekV4dwiZBsN8wGzsPmKFyyr9xXj-fABxaPE4g1FfVBNIi9KTlVd5OwGF-t2CtFfyOsyFifN1dEXgD9c0Zpe4B4kJvI9EJkvahoRcOp6Vo6b5PHaPVHudMO-SX6AaWqY-ZRMDxWWwnoBHcTxLcE2i6wNaB0JjwAY_6hTcRv6_34aEj2-CyXBaZkVdLOGat3OEJSabbc3F3hacdNm02gMe17Hq72D8onABtY9urZWg==)\n[2] [geeksforgeeks.org](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEabc9rroiosqxNrOGcYWeNJONsWukJv41PTFkguygdnGteBVM22mVnrhbDwYmtcV1ArA3WZmPUGM_zuiQYFsYQ-w9-jmOIieqFzNCvUroaccI3ORrhC480f5jvb4hSHdeuHf-ZnD6Hda1_9bFhwK5dkgoL5ceVl411KSlEHV-Gw492qPCYsriAXLU_qrRMTPENP4jekVw2WhhMEeDfonEd8QLbUDUAvQ==)\n[3] [google.dev](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEF-wGLY1URVItEQt3ClquBvYjyL9QyJ8SUlIAvzLUdPAhzlE0vSovO8-1g-Tmtic0pMmq-LYMXwBg8MQxVtMOXJbmr0exawZUC5mWCa4y4n7ofJtP7BMumVNBPC35WqetA4IAbM-kbj7UhYhmbvgB-T2iVYnYvcCRzUv0qdh0zYs8IkxQ6tz6Slz_bSM_AVwv-SLexChkzynN57AD2S2qKACDR6zuXpX9FUirns968Ig==)\n[4] [github.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFPFk_G1