    summary: "The error message \"Cannot set property fetch of #<Window>\" or \"Cannot set property fetch of Window\" typically indicates that a script or library is attempting to reassign or modify the `fetch` function directly on the browser\'s `Window` object. This commonly leads to a `TypeError` because the `window.fetch` property is often configured with a getter, making it a non-writable and non-configurable property in modern browser environments[1][2][3].\n\nThis issue often arises in the following scenarios:\n\n*   **Third-party libraries:** Some JavaScript libraries, particularly those designed for debugging, network request interception, or polyfilling, might try to override the native `fetch` API. For instance, `vConsole` has been identified as a library that can cause this error if it attempts to redefine `window.fetch` directly without checking if it\'s writable[1].\n*   **Environment inconsistencies:** While `fetch` is a native browser API, older Node.js environments did not support it natively, requiring external modules like `node-fetch`[4][5][6]. However, the error mentioning `#<Window>` strongly suggests a browser context.\n*   **Incorrect polyfills or custom overrides:** Developers might implement their own polyfills or custom logic to modify `fetch`\'s behavior, leading to this error if the implementation attempts a direct assignment to `window.fetch`.\n\nTo resolve this error, consider the following approaches:\n\n*   **Update problematic libraries:** If a third-party library is causing the error, check for available updates. Newer versions might include fixes that properly handle the immutability of `window.fetch` by checking its writability before attempting to modify it[1].\n*   **Inspect and modify code attempting to redefine `fetch`:** If you have custom code or a specific library that is trying to reassign `window.fetch`, you can implement a check using `Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor()` to determine if the `fetch` property is writable. If it\'s not, the redefinition attempt should be skipped or handled differently[1].\n*   **Ensure correct environment usage:** If your project involves both browser and Node.js environments (e.g., with frameworks like Next.js), make sure that any `fetch` polyfills or overrides are applied conditionally only in the environment where they are truly needed and compatible.\n\nSources:\n[1] [github.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG0E4qV4cVFm9JN2cEPvOqGfR8MCx5tDQw4B8uF1iu5CBUuEtrhFHaB2p8Mhk1fhLxv5ZD2FPDmGO5RQ61162QKPZy64fpYwRSMJWXR3uFo0uWT28BY0th8wNeYAqMkhOG3E0KViu9Gkfw=)\n[2] [mozilla.org](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG_ARx3Hq6yuzgIZI-npZ2WLakJq0I-zfpJb0xF4KG-onCAq6Qcjx9nvwO9C1DlHOci1d_ziedso6LZb-CvSdQd9eZxRyMiV0RGzHy53JwQefd0bBWl1t5KOpXQ-M9fmaaJGecYlUj73j-7rtaCYZbtpN_pEnRFmpY=)\n[3] [whatwg.org](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEEAfcZLZvflhrvmr4xhPYyWWqdFcjKMn9E2pm2XD1jZZNibhneHJPrXhI1B-RGMA6hKUzByDNSdsQA09TSLTIQ5LBdChPrJPoIu9olXLNIdA0okOLkKVtQSQ==)\n[4] [stackoverflow.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEdFsGf3JKMqv2RJe1ehzATJGcYnlwxLjTOqq-wVG5-AZ3D56PlnAjKQ7gYSvKdp3034NwSltBO-LvZM-kEJLJW_hQ7K1TJhcUNgEQANFrGmKTvs9mMjtLu0hQ1bE-av_0gSD9RTKUyGJEDyJUhQsr8PPorDvP7drnlHCEdFZ34vdN9g7euaT1M2pjt)\n[5] [jetbrains.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF52ZmumHXRwcOQGvmWCZDLjsfxWMAnCJX0z_YrHStjLdA2z_vgJHvrAbFG-XRQG8KrS8lT7q9rtUXn-iKiIqunoUETe_3BPSnnGc4yW1L83mz2HZfYYYU-1c0giFJjHlETz2CtPWl-gy2EqWUQETEMXnwVzo935h6seE-47f8QYPMXei6zp5CJqAjoDaaTAMcpekzqtxLlnAxm7qn7DysF2Em8AfJ-VJZHOK9xreMGUb0x_V-Ki-DUIE6HX58=)\n[6] [manektech.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHHYraSOG7pF0d3Jua4ZxKrCQnXgrm9ZHJrshYvMoZT0fvnW_-4eo4nNsGiybH6ac4-c5adrMJyxVr8M1UtVL6auWHYLAe0HchTgHFw7YwFhg_YMiHft8uBiO2ssyPpYsmCMoztNMyOmdnVixYWLSA6quolvj9dWEPytaQsz33q70ZuFcygahIFU7KBw2bnaBeV-BvMGUx36w==)"
