    summary: "In programming, \"has only a getter\" refers to a property or field that allows its value to be read but not directly modified from outside the object or class it belongs to. The term \"fetch\" typically refers to the process of retrieving data from a source, most commonly in the context of network requests in web development.\n\n### Getter-Only Properties\n\nA \"getter-only\" property, also known as a read-only property, provides a mechanism to access an object\'s internal state without allowing external code to change it directly. This concept promotes encapsulation and helps maintain data integrity within a program. The value of a getter-only property is typically initialized when the object is created (e.g., in a constructor) or set internally by other methods within the same class[1][2][3][4][5].\n\nDifferent programming languages implement getter-only properties in various ways:\n*   **C#**: Read-only auto-properties (introduced in C# 6.0) allow assignments only during declaration or within a constructor. Another approach is to use a private setter, which means the property can be read externally but only modified internally by the class[1][6][2][7].\n*   **Scala**: A `val` field automatically synthesizes a getter but no setter, making it a read-only property[3].\n*   **Kotlin**: Properties automatically have a `get()` function (getter). If a property is mutable, it also has a `set()` function (setter). Read-only properties (declared with `val`) only have a getter[5].\n*   **JavaScript**: While not a strict \"getter-only\" keyword, accessor properties can be defined with only a `get` method, making them read-only from the outside. Attempting to assign a value to such a property would result in an error[8].\n\n### Fetch\n\nIn a general computing context, \"fetch\" means to retrieve data from a specific location or source, such as a database, hard drive, or memory[9][10].\n\nIn web development, \"fetch\" most commonly refers to the **Fetch API**, a modern JavaScript interface for making network requests[11][12][13][14][15][16]. It is used to retrieve resources asynchronously across the network, such as fetching data from application programming interfaces (APIs)[9][13][17][18].\n\nKey characteristics of the Fetch API include:\n*   **Promise-based**: Unlike its predecessor, `XMLHttpRequest`, Fetch uses Promises, which simplifies handling asynchronous operations and makes code more readable[11][12][13].\n*   **HTTP Requests**: It allows web browsers to make various types of HTTP requests (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) to web servers[12][14].\n*   **Global Function**: The `fetch()` function is available globally in both window and worker contexts[11].\n*   **Response Handling**: The `fetch()` method returns a Promise that resolves to a `Response` object. This object represents the server\'s response, and its body can be extracted in various formats, such as JSON or plain text[11][12][13][17].\n*   **Modern Replacement**: The Fetch API is considered a more powerful and flexible replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`[11][13][14][16].\n\nSources:\n[1] [stackoverflow.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEd-64PDrJYdHJsNw7NIPhRnyOrxYudSzoFE9dlMP4MFRmhxZ_SLUNVDPiPYYtiBtGplnEhEtVbUaHHZ-iTvDyj03VfRx1A9Xnz2jNGyvMAXwREFQD4UQvBbuW8EtBjBBIrRHZMSGfUHLWJ5ux12T2PdU7mLeoGPnk8KLXu4H3UzexB5NA9BJ4Cut5H9bQC_POF9s_8AwRg5R4gbk3f9XYwmmlT)\n[2] [microsoft.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGwDw9TSxGd-DTAT3FjagcYiYV2WvLxkzOpuyc00vLKqtab5Jxcp_K3RJNsctmrSoTv1KiAY3JhDYaWbUlQ04t9JCJiY-YIwZbYwUleYKdT0ABkfZQ2M6P7VExLykO7EITjX87FJ6p-l7UyhS8V61jzIVZzzr_qP9UOyHagHZpYcUPAN6y1HXq0XcG4xgB9Bw==)\n[3] [informit.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFP6ioXb6LFJqqAwH46WR6et5dit56CF45B7YkFyVaKIw4xSttDgiR8hP-xI8BeVa4Jaw7DS711AmlhArSvwiIO0Mn2Wd0zLr2-owK9TcLFS6WPQSZq6VaDKvfSGXk7Bncc14L5kkV9IPO1OG4KnldBUDRTwLClttyAl7qV)\n[4] [youtube.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFHboSAxCE1EUaNGhFa3s4ThdoryxW0Dtg_-5PX9aYsxVaw-DSDZ84jjmK9Ut34QcDcTQA_4SZVIVB6nrMPnqGPykUM0tWpm4Grat1QnDpenpM4XeaGJ-Sq4aeid7tR-kCUM0hISX4=)\n[5] [kotlinlang.org](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG7gaFdUpEM8HFfHDL7_R6i3YGB9ZU-JoPVlzmDjgAmO3P5asLzTQAQl0ajjsvoaUF5zl_ivafnn4SjhvoCtluGyg1bXzI8LgADib2mPhhQ7EsjJjpPQPc9VDyOqVzaLvvWN0HZ6Bk=)\n[6] [stackoverflow.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFD_pyEUglwk_980NmoiEYKZFNi4aQ1X98FLyk8gbYVlNSOSSU5i0qPn_VXt6rf9-ruPklVym-j2iZEwF5AwCAC3OYVCKvb21R1lCgi597Ur3IPzFB9btpUMCeQOidXQ76_aS5Ih_wbKtsYZq9K8UqT2gQr0hF8yHyUiAFZ1huQnzpGEaIj7BGZUkcXoA==)\n[7] [medium.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGJrcMaX42H2Z7VeI9h58WZfP-o3_g7aj2ZUhpzoA_Hd4-l2jpYmGdoAonu52UEP_2L4dwHgZSkZCd6ucyo0pyWnH6u8nQVyzrS4d9Rvtn5J2At1HTowgU91oDcbdsl9i6Xx32B74n_qBgsu9gYVN3wIgd6Wpxi2G8UpegXUr_Kd8YAJozsIJlCQRw9OpmQRXwS0qVd6-yVB8IkFWVYF6LNWVuD)\n[8] [javascript.info](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFZtp4fQcZFLKwSTKNtE9eupQibgfMDcig_zg-wAVObRNHKLDruS6IT8_iXmWCv-OCq1om5A_HtKOlMOC3j0D5-LqzL41edLGKtlbg-2irHBdW0dEXbcA4vqKc4jA1ewVRBpJ_SIw==)\n[9] [lenovo.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFRgliZXFoGSKADRy2ooLtGa3CjBCHlLR58UI2PcpM0TkqCQd6SarL3FZBsNGzwqSLl_RMyQATztgjebJR0HbYWbOm7lWd1OMm4YgOAtdYsiqB-m5f9HGAaitmtasFzOxEW08DGgHbXkwSEKGsfdI4=)\n[10] [quora.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFn4RRtOVVh3PzJ05qu3qdjXWtqVsd-GZZRBkhyxp5_CfeSWkLr35Ni-uRPrHPjqWE4UKSIVsoGRL2QV4HEAN6qQ3Y1f3b7T0jrXa6ddwkEgWEYVQnvgNHiljiJMs3uBhE8UgpPyUeByFMVHFxBSLn2XJK5E_91L9-RkA==)\n[11] [mozilla.org](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHgIheiy6SIoKpR5FWvAe1PC3KasGtRJwls5U3CTQRkvjeMZTva0gKuH-DYjKfw2fbfFvgyjxKda3iq2ShiOQT-IaAdStZmCDXvUBQEzsm08xW0_5HPnfQ48aftpe55BHe_up9UR1GzoH6cFEKq5fZMLd3OdBjUGNPDDLLFR7eqO9M