ter on our defined property will ensure successful updates! Subsequent assignments to `window.fetch` will trigger our setter, keeping everything clean. Calling `fetch(...)` will now invoke our getter, which returns the updated reference. This approach appears safe and directly resolves the problem without changing our fetching logic! I\'ve confirmed that `Object.defineProperty` works to redefine `window.fetch`. I\'m going to implement this solution at the top of `src/main.tsx` with a wrapper for the original `window.fetch`.\n\n\n**Refining Entry Point Solution**\n\nI\'m now refining the code placement and implementation for the entry-point polyfill in `src/main.tsx`. This polyfill uses a getter and setter to prevent \"only a getter\" errors from external scripts or mock runners. This includes updating `currentFetch`, and returning it when it is read. This strategy is proving safe and aligns with established patterns for intercepting fetch calls in read-only environments. Positioning the polyfill at the top of `src/main.tsx` ensures it initializes before React.\n\n\n"
