    thinking: "**Investigating the TypeError**\n\nI\'m currently trying to understand the \"Uncaught TypeError: Cannot set property fetch of #<Window> which has only a getter\" error. I\'ve realized that the issue arises when attempting to redefine the `fetch` property on the `Window` object, which is problematic in certain browsers or sandbox iframe configurations. My focus now is on pinpointing the specific environments where this behavior manifests.\n\n\n**Analyzing the Code**\n\nI\'ve zeroed in on the `Object.defineProperty` call in `src/main.tsx`. It looks like I was attempting to redefine `window.fetch` using a getter and setter. However, it looks like that specific call might be the root cause, as it might be directly throwing the `TypeError`. I also need to investigate if someone else is setting `window.fetch`.\n\n\n**Pinpointing the Assignment**\n\nI\'m now investigating potential code that\'s directly assigning a value to `window.fetch`. It seems the issue isn\'t our `Object.defineProperty` call, thanks to the `try/catch` block. I\'m focusing on external polyfills or libraries like `@protobufjs/fetch` or the sandbox environment itself, or a browser extension interfering. I\'m also looking for any direct assignments within the workspace or test suite, as assigning to a read-only getter like `window.fetch` throws the exact error. I am also checking whether we might be attempting to define it on `window.prototype` or on `Window` directly.\n\n\n**Re-evaluating the Timing**\n\nOkay, I\'ve re-examined the timing. The `TypeError` appeared *before* my recent change in `src/main.tsx` and the successful build. This suggests the issue isn\'t directly related to the new getter/setter code. I need to pivot and search for other factors. The prompt in this turn said \"`.`\", suggesting the problem is resolved, or the tests are passing. I\'ll need to confirm that it\'s gone for good.\n\n\n"
