    thinking: "**Understanding Fetch Property**\n\nI\'ve learned that `window.fetch` isn\'t directly configurable in modern browsers like Chrome. It\'s a non-configurable getter defined on `Window.prototype`. This explains some of the constraints I\'ve been seeing and clarifies its behavior.\n\n\n**Analyzing Assignment Attempts**\n\nI\'ve confirmed that direct redefinition of `window.fetch` via `Object.defineProperty` results in a `TypeError`, as expected. Also, I\'ve just run a series of `grep` commands across the codebase, including `node_modules` and `src`, searching for assignments to `window.fetch`, `self.fetch`, `globalThis.fetch`, and `global.fetch`. The results were negative, indicating no such assignments exist. So, I have moved one step closer in the debugging process, and can make assumptions on that.\n\n\n**Investigating Dependency Impact**\n\nI\'m now digging into potential dependencies that might be influencing `fetch` behavior. I\'ve switched my focus from the build output to a deeper dive into the `package.json` and `package-lock.json` files. My initial concern was about direct assignments, which I have determined are not the case. I\'ve identified the presence of `@google/genai` (which is not relevant for this application) and, crucially, `node-fetch` within the dependency tree. I am investigating the usage of `node-fetch` in the project.\n\n\n**Uncovering Proxy Mechanism**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the possibility of an environment-level interception of `fetch`. I\'m exploring the idea that the AI Studio platform\'s preview environment, likely via a sandboxing script, or an iframe proxying/mocking setup, might be intercepting `window.fetch`. I suspect this interception is done to manage network requests for telemetry, proxying, caching, or mock data. I\'ve noted a TypeError which reinforces this line of reasoning.\n\n\n**Defining Fetch Interception**\n\nI\'ve made a breakthrough. I realized the TypeError is likely thrown when the platform script attempts to override `window.fetch`. My new strategy: define a configurable/writable `fetch` *very early* in the process, perhaps on `Window.prototype` using a `<script>` tag in the `<head>`, to preempt the platform\'s script\'s attempt. This could allow the sandbox to work without an error. Let\'s see if this works!\n\n\n**Testing `window` Overriding**\n\nI\'m now investigating whether directly defining `fetch` on the `window` object can bypass the platform\'s potential interception. I\'ve confirmed that `fetch` is a configurable and writable property on `Window.prototype`, so direct assignment should be feasible. I\'ll test overriding it on the instance `window` itself. This could determine if I can create an early interception that the platform script can\'t interfere with.\n\n\n**Exploring Configuration Restrictions**\n\nI\'m now investigating the implications of a getter-only `fetch` property. This restriction likely means `window.fetch` is non-configurable, so I\'m researching how this affects attempts to redefine or assign a new value. My focus has shifted to the sandboxing environment and potential scenarios where a getter-only definition might be present, possibly within an iframe or through a browser extension. I am testing a range of solutions to intercept the getter definition.\n\n\n"
